We recommended the following:

The Inventory Committee shall conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and reconcile the local road inventory with the records of the accounting office;

The Municipal GSO must maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for each road network;

The Municipal Engineer shall provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The Municipal Accountant shall ensure that the transfer of all local roads to the Account- Road Networks shall be completed as at year-end.

We recommended the following:
The Inventory Committee shall conduct a physical inventory of the all the local road network under the LGU’s jurisdiction and reconcile the local road inventory with the records of the accounting office;
The Municipal GSO must maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for each road network;
The Municipal Engineer shall provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for all its local road networks with the help of the Municipal Assessor on the assessment of road lot component;
The Municipal Accountant shall ensure that all local road networks and its component will be recorded in the book of accounts.

We recommended that the Management:
1.  Direct the concerned personnel to prepare the required summary list together with the required supporting documents and reports on cash donations and in-kind and submit the same to COA;
2.  Post the reports on the receipt and utilization of DRRMF sourced from GAA and donations in cash and in-kind in the LGU website;
3.   Instruct the GSO to coordinate with the MSWDO and Mayor’s Office with regards to the donated items to be able to maintain inventory list thereof; and
4.  Strictly adhere to COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009 on the accounting and reporting guidelines of cash and in-kind donations.

We recommended that the Management instruct the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to:

for reconciling items arising from errors in deposits, the Municipal Treasurer shall verify these items in the RCDs and make necessary actions based on the results of the verification;

for the reconciling items that occurred due to the errors in posting by both the treasury and accounting office, adjustments shall be made accordingly;

closely supervise the personnel assigned in the depositing and posting of cash transactions to prevent the accumulation of errors that may affect the accuracy and validity of the cash in bank; and

checks outstanding for two years or more shall be treated as surplus adjustment and prepare a separate registry to monitor the outstanding checks reverted to the cash in bank.

We recommended that the Management:

Reclassify the completed projects from Construction in Progress to their proper asset accounts and recognize depreciation expenses retrospectively;

Require the municipal assessor to prepare the inventory of all lands owned by the Municipality and the accountant shall record them in the books after all the documents proving ownership is presented;

Conduct physical count before closing of books and reconcile all the discrepancies noted; 

Submit to our office the request for inspection and appraisal of all damaged and unserviceable items and the request for relief from accountability for all missing properties; and

Refrain from disposing government properties without prior inspection of the Commission.

We recommended that the Management take the following measures:

Refrain from charging transactions not related to DRRM Fund to make room for activities geared for disaster-preparedness and resiliency;

Assign a bigger and safer storage area of the relief goods and ensure that properties be handled properly;

Require the Property and Supply Officer to include in the inventory report the undistributed relief goods and agricultural supplies while the Municipal Accountant shall only record the stockpiled goods as expense only upon distribution to disaster-affected beneficiaries and submission of distribution list of beneficiaries as basis of preparation of Journal Entry Voucher;

The Municipal DRRM Officer shall regularly maintain the LDRRM Plan for unexpended balance and monitor its implementation;

Refrain from realigning the LDRRM fund to new expenditure items without the appropriation ordinance pursuant to Section 305 (a) of RA 7160 and Section 6.5 of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC 2013-1.

We recommended that the Management:

Monitor properly the transfer of rights over the occupation of the block tiendas and identify who among the occupants are non-members and execute Contract of Lease accordingly with proper endorsement from the Association based on the Compromise Agreement;

Review the Compromise Agreement and the accompanying Contract of Lease and identify whether occupants of blocks 1, 2 and 97-100 were rightfully covered therewith, and if not covered, reassess the lease contracts and make supplemental agreement based on the Code of Economic Enterprise; 

Reassess the amount of the monthly rate based on the Contract of Lease and the Code of Economic Enterprise;

Make necessary actions over the collections of the delinquencies and impose sanctions accordingly; 

Make an investigation on the alleged missing index cards of payments; and

Record in the books the total amount collectible from block tiendas occupants and create individual ledger to each occupant for proper monitoring.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Instruct the Municipal Engineer and the MPDC to install project billboards at the project sites containing complete information as soon as the award has been made in accordance with COA Circular 2013-004;

If the project billboards were included as pay item of the projects, require the contractor to install the required billboards, otherwise, the Municipal Accountant shall deduct from the claims of the contractors the total cost of the billboards;

Inform the Office of the Auditor when project signboard was already installed as prescribed under Section 3.1 of COA Circular 2013-004;

Strictly implement the provisions of COA Circular 2013-004 on the information and publicity on Programs/Projects/Activities of government agencies as well as the provisions of law on full public disclosure policy.

We recommended that the Management:

Submit to the Auditor the contract documents of the projects within five days after perfection;

Submit the purchase orders on time and ensure that the date of delivery, unit cost, date of receipt by the supplier and other necessary information are supplied;

Strictly follow the time schedules in every stage of procurement, scrutinize the submitted bid documents during post-qualification, and submit the lacking documents for each project; 

Refrain from using Small-Value Procurement as method in leasing venues and prepare the technical specification and rating factors in accordance to Annex H of the IRR of RA 9184; 

exercise prudence in the disbursement of government funds and the practice of letting other associations organize the activities of the municipality as to not circumvent the rules and regulations of the procurement process of the government should be discouraged; 

Conduct market study and employ control measures on prescribing rates for catering services; and

Follow at all times the IRR of RA 9184 and all other regulations relative to government procurement.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Secure from the GSIS GIF all insurances or bonds covering properties, contracts, rights of action, and other insurable risks;

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to include in the annual budget the amount of premiums for the general insurance of all insurable properties of the Municipality;

For faster implementation, instruct all heads of office to provide the Municipal GSO with the list of insurable assets in their respective offices; and

Require the Municipal GSO to consolidate and confirm the reports submitted by each office. The Property Inventory Form shall then be prepared and submit a copy to the Audit Team on or before April 30 of each year.

We recommended that the Management:

Deduct from the salaries of the employees their unpaid salary loans;

Send demand letters to those individuals who already resigned or retired from government service, requiring them to immediately settle their unpaid salary loans;

Record all lumped balances during conversion of the accounting system to their appropriate account; and

Ensure that government funds are properly safeguarded against loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition.

We recommended that the Management:

Conduct inspection on the building and assess whether it is still serviceable, and if verified to be serviceable, make necessary plans on how to maximize the utilization of the building;

Require adequate preparation and training to the implementing units when it comes to livelihood projects prior to implementation;

Monitor and evaluate regularly the operations of all government projects and make necessary actions on how to improve the operations; and

Bear prudence in the preparation and planning of the projects, taking into consideration all aspects that would affect the implementation of the projects to ensure its optimal use and to prevent wastage of government funds.

