We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the following officials of the Municipality to undertake the following measures:

a. Reclassify the Property, Plant and Equipment identified as Inventories to the proper accounts;
b. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment on annual basis and for Inventories for every six (6) months;
c. Submit separate Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property;
d. Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare the Inventory Report using the prescribed format, Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for Inventories and Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) for Property, Plant and Equipment and submit the same to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of the following year;
e. The inventory listing of the equipment should be compared with the property card maintained by the Municipal General Services Office as against the equipment ledger cards maintained by the Office of the Municipal Accountant and the total thereof should be reconciled;
f. All discrepancies noted between physical and book inventories must be investigated, cleared and reconciled. If necessary, written explanation should be required from accountable and responsible person. In addition, the Office of the Municipal Accountant should continue its effort to locate pertinent source documents to reduce the unidentified balances in the property ledger cards, if any, in order to render a complete and accurate financial report.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Issue a final demand letter to all accountable officers for the immediate liquidation/ settlement of their unliquidated cash advances and in case of non-compliance, withhold from their salaries the total amount due for those who are still active and find any legal remedies to compel the liquidation of cash advances for those who are not already connected with the LGU;
b. Ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at year end;
c. Discontinue granting of cash advances to officers and employees with outstanding obligations; and
d. Make necessary actions for the proper reporting of dormant accounts by submitting request for write-off of dormant accounts and its underlying supporting documents to prove that the accounts are no longer collectible.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. review the existence of the accounts with negative balances and make necessary adjusting entries;
b. make necessary actions to be provided with copies of the debit memos relating to the unrecorded loan repayments;
c. exert extra effort in retrieving the transaction documents for the unreconciled items and make adjustments thereof, if necessary; and 
d. monitor closely the preparation of the financial statements and ensure that the reliability and accuracy of its accounts to present fairly in the FS.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to:
1. follow strictly the period prescribed for every stages of the procurement process;
2. carefully examine the validity of the licenses and clearances of the prospective bidders during the post-qualification process; 
3. issue necessary Supplemental/ Bid Bulletin upon modification of the contentions of the Bidding Documents;
4. require the winning bidder to submit the necessary documents prior to contract signing; and
5. strictly adhere with pertinent provisions of the Revised IRR of Republic Act No. 9184.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the concerned officials to:
a. conduct the bidding for the infrastructure projects earlier than the last quarter of the year;
b. strengthen peace and order programs especially to the construction sites;
c. furnish the Audit Team of the copies of suspension orders and its supporting documents;
d. make necessary measures to correct the construction defects 
e. submit the perfected contracts and the supporting documents within the prescribed period; and
f. monitor closely the implementation of infrastructure projects and ensure quality and useful completed projects.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the concerned officials to:
a. review the collectability of the receivables from the consumers of the water system and submit Request for Write-off if those are proven uncollectible;
b. fast track the implementation of the projects for the new water system from its procurement until construction;
c. conduct analysis of facility utilization and facility cost audit to identify the rates of providing the services for the Medical/Diagnostic; and
d. apply the provisions of the Manual to ensure the quality of the services provided and to generate satisfactory income.

